item.title: Incest By Proxy - Feel Like Death 2K6
item.description:
Song: Feel Like Death 2K6 Album: Methhead Mechanic Single

I once knew true love. Once... maybe twice. And when I was in love I could never imagine that it would go away in a fleeting instant with no warning. With her in my life I was complete. Without her I am complete, but less enthusiastic and more depressed. I had forgotten why it was I loved her, and at times I thought my life might be better without her. It is not. My attempts to remember things and events from our years together are becoming more and more futile as the days go on. The name of the park in Marquette off of Hawley which is also referred to by a number. The number I cannot remember though I drove the road almost daily smoking joints and turning around in the parking lot of that park I cannot remember the name of. I have forgotten which factory it was where we harassed the employees at 4 A.M. on our first date. There are thousands of little memories that I am loosing with every passing day. Memories of things we did alone. Memories that only the two of us share. These will soon be gone. She was truly my best friend for a solid 5 years and 3 months. We were inseparable, yet at some point, undetectable by myself, she decided to leave me forever. To cut all contact with me. Things were always rough between us. I must admit to this. We were arrogant and believed we were handling our problems properly. I mean, we both had psychology degrees after all. How were we unable to see how unhealthy our relationship had become? If only I had been more sensitive to her needs. If only she had told me what they were. If only we would have sought counseling. If only she would have gone with. If only we had made our lives more exciting. If only she had suggested something interesting to do. If only she had told me what she was feeling in a calm manner rather than calling her parents who have always hated me. Her parents who, unlike any other girl I've ever dated, have always made me uncomfortable. Her parents who never did a thing to help us. Her parents who said they would disown her if she ever saw me again. Unconditional love, right. Funny... After all of this... I still feel something. I also feel sick. We both full-on cried last fall after watching Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind. I came home from work to find her in tears. She told me I needed to watch the movie with her. I'm no fan of romance movies, but I watched it anyway. Yeah, and it made me cry... really cry... hard... for at least an hour. Now we are experiencing what that movie was all about. To succeed in a relationship the two partners must both be aware of the things that will doom the relationship. It's not enough to just say, “I love you... you are the most interesting and attractive person in the world... I know you love me more than anyone else in the world... Even if you were to sleep with someone else I would trust you could never love them as you do me”. To participate in a truly deep relationship it is important to say (and believe) such things. Even more important is to be aware of what your partner is feeling and how to make them feel better. You must find a way to know and what to do about it. Some people are very open, perhaps I was just getting to that point with her in the past year. I don't think she ever fully opened up. I believe there was much more to know about her. I wish I'd had all of her, right down to her most deeply hidden thoughts, desires, and neuroses. We had finally moved to where we had always wanted to live together. Then came the health insurance, and with it came the pills. And with the pills came the fear, the fear that she would hurt herself or destroy her life. I did everything I could and more than I should have to make her stop. Unfortunately, it was futile. But there was always fear about one thing or another. It used to be fear that she didn't love me as much as she said. Later it became fear of failure in college (totally unsubstantiated and my fault). Later a fear of failure in the real world, money and such. When I became fearful and could do nothing about it, I became frustrated. This frustration led to anger, and my anger made her frustrated as she did not know how to calm me. Her frustration led to anger and ultimately we became aggressive toward one another. Now, regardless of the fact that we shared so many similarities, we can never be together. It will be a difficult thing for either of us to ever find someone we can love as much as we loved each other. So much of our personalities have been formed around each other. The bond is strong and will never die. We will always remember what little we can of each other, and unfortunately due to the reactions of our friends and family most will be bad. Especially since communication between the two of us is now forbidden. I'm not ALL hardcore. I still know what love is.
